4-chloro-7-nitrobenzo-2-oxa-1,3-diazole (NBD-Cl) is a nonfluorescent reagent, but can react with thiols and aliphatic amines to form fluorescent and colored adducts [12–14]. For instance, NBD-Cl can react with l-cysteine (Cys) and generate highly fluorescent 7-N-cysteinyl-4-nitrobenz-2-oxa-1,3-diazole (NBD-Cys) based on nucleophilic substitution and Smiles rearrangement reactions (
                        Scheme S1
                     ) [12–14]. Currently, NBD-Cl has been extensively used to synthesize new fluorescent probes [15,16]. In addition, NBD-Cl has been widely used to label various biomolecules [14,17,18]. Despite that NBD-Cl can show colorimetric and fluorescent responses to various thiols and amines, the analytical application field of NBD-Cl based reaction is still too narrow, which is confined to detect analytes involved in NBD-Cl based reaction [19]. Any analyte irrelative to the NBD-Cl based reaction has not been detected yet. We anticipate that a novel NBD-Cl based platform for colorimetric and fluorescent immunoassay might be constructed by coupling the NBD-Cl based reaction with immunological recognition.

We studied the specificity of the proposed method. Due to the high immunoaffinity between the anti-S. aureus antibody and antigen on the surfaces of S. aureus cells, the colorimetric and fluorescent signals for the detection of S. aureus are much higher than those for the detection of E. coli O157:H7, S. spp., and L. monocytogenes (Fig. 5
                        ), though the concentrations of other bacterial samples is 10 times that of S. aureus. Colorimetric and fluorescent detection of S. aureus in milk samples was carried out. As shown in Table 1
                        , the recoveries are between 93 and 106%, indicating that colorimetric and fluorescent detection of S. aureus in real samples using the proposed method is feasible.
